            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Saoura is an administrative region in southwestern Algeria stretching along the Oued Saoura, which is formed from the confluence of the Oued Guir and Oued Zouzfana at Igli. The Oued Saoura forms the western border of the Grand Erg Occidental.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The dialect of Saoura covers the area of the oases of Béchar, Abadla, Igli, Mazzer, Béni Abbès, Kerkaz, and Ksabi.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:E9XITWZC">Grand’Henry (1979)</rs> is a short grammatical sketch of the dialect of 
               Saoura, including phonological, morphological, and syntactic information. In the conclusion he characterizes the dialect of 
               Saoura on the basis of the classification of Algerian dialects made by <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:3YXEQ5II">Cantineau (1940)</rs>. 
               <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:XP3EXGA8">Grand’Henry (1980)</rs> offers a very brief overview of the results of a dialectological 
               survey of the Saoura region.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">There are two studies specifically on the dialect of the oasis of Béchar in the Saoura: 
               <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:9BHX3FT3">Bouamrane (1994)</rs> discusses lexical variation, and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:A3XY8KI9">Fezzioui (2013)</rs> phonological 
               and morphological as well as lexical variation in that dialect.</p>
            </div>
